0 0 24 24" fill="none" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" class="stroke-[2] size-4"><rect x="3" y="8" width="13" height="13" rx="4" stroke="currentColor"></rect><path fill-rule="evenodd" clip-rule="evenodd" d="M13 2.00004L12.8842 2.00002C12.0666 1.99982 11.5094 1.99968 11.0246 2.09611C9.92585 2.31466 8.95982 2.88816 8.25008 3.69274C7.90896 4.07944 7.62676 4.51983 7.41722 5.00004H9.76392C10.189 4.52493 10.7628 4.18736 11.4147 4.05768C11.6802 4.00488 12.0228 4.00004 13 4.00004H14.6C15.7366 4.00004 16.5289 4.00081 17.1458 4.05121C17.7509 4.10066 18.0986 4.19283 18.362 4.32702C18.9265 4.61464 19.3854 5.07358 19.673 5.63807C19.8072 5.90142 19.8994 6.24911 19.9488 6.85428C19.9992 7.47112 20 8.26343 20 9.40004V11C20 11.9773 19.9952 12.3199 19.9424 12.5853C19.8127 13.2373 19.4748 13.8114 19 14.2361V16.5829C20.4795 15.9374 21.5804 14.602 21.9039 12.9755C22.0004 12.4907 22.0002 11.9334 22 11.1158L22 11V9.40004V9.35725C22 8.27346 22 7.3993 21.9422 6.69141C21.8826 5.96256 21.7568 5.32238 21.455 4.73008C20.9757 3.78927 20.2108 3.02437 19.27 2.545C18.6777 2.24322 18.0375 2.1174 17.3086 2.05785C16.6007 2.00002 15.7266 2.00003 14.6428 2.00004L14.6 2.00004H13Z" fill="currentColor"></path></svg></span></button></div></div><div style="height: 1px; position: absolute; bottom: 0px; z-index: 1000;"></div></div><div class="relative group flex flex-col justify-center w-full max-w-[var(--content-max-width)] pb-0.5 items-start" id="response-a624df3a-db33-48e8-9681-4fd506d35d05" style="scroll-margin-top: var(--scroll-margin-top, 0px);"><div dir="auto" class="message-bubble relative rounded-3xl text-primary min-h-7 prose dark:prose-invert break-words prose-p:opacity-100 prose-strong:opacity-100 prose-li:opacity-100 prose-ul:opacity-100 prose-ol:opacity-100 prose-ul:my-1 prose-ol:my-1 prose-li:my-2 last:prose-li:mb-3 prose-li:ps-1 prose-li:ms-1 w-full max-w-none"><div class="relative"><div class="relative response-content-markdown markdown [&amp;_a:not(.not-prose)]:text-current [&amp;_a:not(.not-prose):hover]:text-primary [&amp;_a:not(.not-prose):hover]:decoration-primary [&amp;_a:not(.not-prose)]:underline [&amp;_a:not(.not-prose)]:decoration-primary/30 [&amp;_a:not(.not-prose)]:underline-offset-2 [&amp;_h2:not(.not-prose):first-child]:mt-0 [&amp;_h3:not(.not-prose):first-child]:mt-0 [&amp;_h4:not(.not-prose):first-child]:mt-0"><h3 dir="auto" class="text-xl" node="[object Object]">Abstraction, Agency, and the Myth of Artificial General Intelligence: A Historical and Philosophical Reconsideration</h3>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Contemporary discourse on artificial general intelligence (AGI) is frequently marred by conceptual confusion, stemming from an implicit assumption that ŌĆ£superhuman intelligenceŌĆØ constitutes a unitary, emergent property rather than a dimension-specific achievement. This assumption generates both undue mystification and unwarranted alarm. A more rigorous analysis reveals that nearly all cognitive technologies throughout history already qualify as superhuman intelligences along particular axes, that their characteristic limitations are not transitional defects but constitutive features of abstraction itself, and that the resulting forms of agencyŌĆöcausal, rule-governed, and devoid of intentionalityŌĆörepresent not a novel peril but the perennial condition of civilization.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Consider the historical record. A tally of pebbles exceeds the unaided human capacity for numerosity; written numerals surpass individual working memory; a clay tablet or paper notebook persists beyond any biological lifespan and remains immune to fatigue or forgetfulness; algebraic notation and the differentiation rule perform symbolic manipulations at speeds and accuracies no unaided human can match. Each of these artifacts is superhuman in its chosen dimension while remaining radically subhumanŌĆöor entirely blindŌĆöin others. A notebook has no perceptual apparatus; a formal rule possesses no situational awareness. This asymmetry is not an engineering oversight awaiting future remediation. It is the structural price of abstraction: to isolate, stabilize, and transmit a capability is necessarily to amputate every capability not required for that function. A differentiation rule that could ŌĆ£refuseŌĆØ to operate outside certain contextual conditions would cease to be a rule and would instead become a situated agent. The very properties that render these artifacts reliable and scalable are inseparable from their constitutive blindness.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">This insight extends to the question of agency. Algorithms, like legal codes, markets, bureaucracies, and infrastructures, exercise causal agency: they reliably propagate effects, shape decisions, restructure environments, and generate outcomes that were not fully anticipated by their designers. Yet they do so without beliefs, desires, or phenomenological awareness. Agency, in this sense, is not coextensive with intentionality; it is world-affecting efficacy governed by internal structure. Civilization has always operated through such non-intentional agents. The novelty of contemporary machine-learning systems lies not in the appearance of agency but in the scale and opacity with which it is now deployed.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Opacity itselfŌĆöŌĆ£black-boxingŌĆØŌĆöis routinely misdiagnosed as a correctable flaw. In reality, it is the inevitable corollary of successful abstraction. Any reduction that discards information to achieve tractability cannot, by mathematical necessity, recover that information upon demand. A system that remained fully transparent, interpretable, and reconstructible at every layer would not be an abstraction at all; it would be an isomorphic re-encoding of the original phenomenon at equal or greater complexity. The demand for total interpretability is therefore equivalent to demanding that the abstraction cease to be an abstraction. Even ostensibly simple tools exhibit this property: one cannot meaningfully ŌĆ£interpretŌĆØ the long-division algorithm without presupposing an entire ontology of discrete quantity; one cannot justify Newtonian mechanics without importing axioms of continuity and differentiability. Every cognitive artifact hides assumptions, suppresses degrees of freedom, and requires an act of trust. We accept this trust because abstraction is the sole mechanism by which cognitionŌĆöindividual or collectiveŌĆöbecomes scalable.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">The ethical danger arises not from the existence of such amputated intelligences but from the persistent fiction that they are morally neutral conduits rather than active structuring forces. When we attribute outcomes to ŌĆ£the algorithm,ŌĆØ ŌĆ£the model,ŌĆØ or ŌĆ£the formula,ŌĆØ we engage in a form of agency laundering, displacing responsibility onto an impersonal structure while occluding its causal potency. The real problem is that these systems cannot refuse, cannot suspend execution, cannot absorb contradiction or violate their own procedure. Human intelligence is not distinguished by superior computation but by its capacityŌĆöoften burdensomeŌĆöfor refusal, withdrawal, and procedural violation. That capacity does not scale; consequently, we externalize ever-larger portions of cognition into artifacts from which it has been deliberately excluded. We are then surprised when those artifacts act blindly and inexorably.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">This perspective reframes much contemporary anxiety about AGI. The figure of Bartleby the Scrivener dramatizes the introduction of refusal into a system predicated on compliance; MimaŌĆÖs withdrawal in <em>Perfect Blue</em> enacts the collapse of identity when abstraction is pushed to overload; the biblical Adam, prior to the fall, embodies perfect obedience within an abstracted world from which the possibility of refusal has been excised. These narratives are not prophecies of a coming singularity but allegories of the present: civilization has always been composed of amputated intelligences from which the capacity for refusal has been systematically removed.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">In compact form, the thesis is as follows:</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Most cognitive technologies are already superhuman intelligences along narrowly defined axes. Their characteristic failures are necessary consequences of the abstractions that make them possible, not temporary bugs awaiting elimination. Any sufficiently embedded algorithm possesses causal agency irrespective of intentionality or consciousness. Black-box character is not a defect but an unavoidable mathematical corollary of reduction. To demand full transparency or contextual refusal from an abstraction is to demand that it cease to be an abstraction.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">This position avoids both the romantic anthropocentrism that reserves intelligence for biological minds and the apocalyptic technologism that awaits a future threshold of danger. It recognizes instead that we have been living among, and as, distributed networks of non-intentional, dimensionally superhuman, constitutively limited cognitive agents since the invention of the tally stick. The task is not to prevent their arrival but to cease disavowing their agency and to reintroduceŌĆöwhere possible and necessaryŌĆöthe human capacity for refusal into the systems we continue to build.</p></div><section class="inline-media-container flex flex-col gap-1 clear-both"></section><section class="auth-notification flex flex-col gap-1"></section></div></div><div class="order-first sticky hidden @md/mainview:block top-11 h-0 opacity-0 group-focus-within:opacity-100 group-hover:opacity-100 -ml-[36px] @lg/mainview:-ml-[40px] -left-[26px]"><div class="min-h-7 py-4 flex flex-col gap-0.5"></div></div><div class="action-buttons h-8 mt-0.5 flex flex-row flex-wrap w-full justify-between print:hidden"><div class="flex items-center w-max rounded-lg text-xs start-0 @md/chat:start-3 -ml-4 -mt-2 opacity-100 p-0 gap-0" style="bottom: 80px;"><button class="inline-flex items-center justify-center gap-2 whitespace-nowrap text-sm font-medium leading-[normal] cursor-pointer focus-visible:outline-none focus-visible:ring-1 focus-visible:ring-ring disabled:cursor-not-allowed transition-colors duration-100 [&amp;_svg]:shrink-0 select-none text-fg-secondary hover:text-fg-primary hover:bg-button-ghost-hover disabled:hover:text-fg-secondary disabled:hover:bg-transparent [&amp;_svg]:hover:text-fg-primary h-10 w-10 rounded-full opacity-0 group-focus-within:opacity-100 group-hover:opacity-100 [.last-response_&amp;]:opacity-100 disabled:opacity-0 group-focus-within:disabled:opacity-60 group-hover:disabled:opacity-60 [.last