&amp;_a:not(.not-prose)]:text-current [&amp;_a:not(.not-prose):hover]:text-primary [&amp;_a:not(.not-prose):hover]:decoration-primary [&amp;_a:not(.not-prose)]:underline [&amp;_a:not(.not-prose)]:decoration-primary/30 [&amp;_a:not(.not-prose)]:underline-offset-2 [&amp;_h2:not(.not-prose):first-child]:mt-0 [&amp;_h3:not(.not-prose):first-child]:mt-0 [&amp;_h4:not(.not-prose):first-child]:mt-0"><h3 dir="auto" class="text-xl" node="[object Object]">Comparison: The Abstraction/Agency Thesis vs. Graham HarmanŌĆÖs Object-Oriented Ontology (OOO)</h3>




























































<div class="relative"><div class="absolute top-1 right-1 z-10 print:hidden"><div class="flex flex-row gap-0.5"><button class="inline-flex items-center justify-center gap-2 whitespace-nowrap text-sm font-medium leading-[normal] cursor-pointer focus-visible:outline-none focus-visible:ring-1 focus-visible:ring-ring disabled:opacity-60 disabled:cursor-not-allowed transition-colors duration-100 [&amp;_svg]:shrink-0 select-none text-fg-secondary hover:text-fg-primary hover:bg-button-ghost-hover disabled:hover:text-fg-secondary disabled:hover:bg-transparent [&amp;_svg]:hover:text-fg-primary h-8 w-8 rounded-full dark:bg-surface-l1 dark:text-text-l1 dark:hover:bg-surface-l2" type="button" aria-label="Copy" data-state="closed"><span style="opacity: 1; transform: none;"><svg width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" class="stroke-[2] size-4"><rect x="3" y="8" width="13" height="13" rx="4" stroke="currentColor"></rect><path fill-rule="evenodd" clip-rule="evenodd" d="M13 2.00004L12.8842 2.00002C12.0666 1.99982 11.5094 1.99968 11.0246 2.09611C9.92585 2.31466 8.95982 2.88816 8.25008 3.69274C7.90896 4.07944 7.62676 4.51983 7.41722 5.00004H9.76392C10.189 4.52493 10.7628 4.18736 11.4147 4.05768C11.6802 4.00488 12.0228 4.00004 13 4.00004H14.6C15.7366 4.00004 16.5289 4.00081 17.1458 4.05121C17.7509 4.10066 18.0986 4.19283 18.362 4.32702C18.9265 4.61464 19.3854 5.07358 19.673 5.63807C19.8072 5.90142 19.8994 6.24911 19.9488 6.85428C19.9992 7.47112 20 8.26343 20 9.40004V11C20 11.9773 19.9952 12.3199 19.9424 12.5853C19.8127 13.2373 19.4748 13.8114 19 14.2361V16.5829C20.4795 15.9374 21.5804 14.602 21.9039 12.9755C22.0004 12.4907 22.0002 11.9334 22 11.1158L22 11V9.40004V9.35725C22 8.27346 22 7.3993 21.9422 6.69141C21.8826 5.96256 21.7568 5.32238 21.455 4.73008C20.9757 3.78927 20.2108 3.02437 19.27 2.545C18.6777 2.24322 18.0375 2.1174 17.3086 2.05785C16.6007 2.00002 15.7266 2.00003 14.6428 2.00004L14.6 2.00004H13Z" fill="currentColor"></path></svg></span></button></div></div><div dir="auto" class="table-container relative group/table clear-both overflow-scroll flex flex-row" style="mask-image: linear-gradient(to right, black 85%, 92.5%, transparent 100%); mask-composite: add;"><div class="scroll-gradient-sentinel" style="height: 100%; width: 1px; left: 0px; flex-shrink: 0;"></div><table dir="auto" class="w-fit min-w-[calc(var(--content-width)-13px)] [&amp;&gt;thead&gt;tr&gt;th:last-child]:pr-8"><thead class="sticky [top:var(--thead-sticky-top)] [&amp;_th]:h-10 [background-color:var(--thead-bg-color)] [box-shadow:0_1px_0_0_var(--thead-border-b-color)] border-b-0" node="[object Object]"><tr class="border-primary/10" node="[object Object]"><th class="break-words" data-col-size="sm" node="[object Object]">Dimension</th><th class="break-words" data-col-size="lg" node="[object Object]">Graham HarmanŌĆÖs Object-Oriented Ontology (OOO)</th><th class="break-words" data-col-size="lg" node="[object Object]">Abstraction/Agency Thesis (present work)</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr class="border-primary/10" node="[object Object]"><td class="break-words" data-col-size="sm" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Core metaphysical move</td><td class="break-words" data-col-size="lg" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Radical withdrawal: every object (human, hammer, atom, algorithm, nation-state) is real and withdraws from all relations and all access.</td><td class="break-words" data-col-size="lg" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Radical amputation: only abstractions (tools, algorithms, formulas, bureaucracies) are constitutively withdrawn/amputated; humans are not withdrawn in the same way.</td></tr><tr class="border-primary/10" node="[object Object]"><td class="break-words" data-col-size="sm" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Status of relations</td><td class="break-words" data-col-size="lg" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Relations are vicarious and sensual translations; the real object always exceeds every relation and every profile.</td><td class="break-words" data-col-size="lg" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Relations are compressive reductions; abstractions work by discarding degrees of freedom that cannot be recovered without destroying scalability.</td></tr><tr class="border-primary/10" node="[object Object]"><td class="break-words" data-col-size="sm" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Agency</td><td class="break-words" data-col-size="lg" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Distributed to everything: a hammer acts, a poem acts, a corporation acts. Agency is not limited to intentionality or life.</td><td class="break-words" data-col-size="lg" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Distributed, but only to systems with persistent, generalizing, constraining internal structure. Mere withdrawn objects do not automatically act.</td></tr><tr class="border-primary/10" node="[object Object]"><td class="break-words" data-col-size="sm" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Withdrawal / opacity</td><td class="break-words" data-col-size="lg" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Ontological and universal: no object is ever fully present to another. Even a rock withdraws from the flame that melts it.</td><td class="break-words" data-col-size="lg" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Epistemic and selective: opacity is the mathematical price paid only by abstractions that achieve scalability through reduction. Humans, animals, ecosystems are not ŌĆ£withdrawnŌĆØ in this sense.</td></tr><tr class="border-primary/10" node="[object Object]"><td class="break-words" data-col-size="sm" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Human exceptionalism</td><td class="break-words" data-col-size="lg" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Completely rejected: humans are just one object among others; no privileged interiority.</td><td class="break-words" data-col-size="lg" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Reintroduced negatively: humans are the only entities that retain the non-scalable capacity for refusal, procedural violation, and meta-level suspension.</td></tr><tr class="border-primary/10" node="[object Object]"><td class="break-words" data-col-size="sm" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Black boxes</td><td class="break-words" data-col-size="lg" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">All objects are eternally black-boxed to everything else. Opening is impossible in principle.</td><td class="break-words" data-col-size="lg" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Black boxes are engineered achievements of reduction; partial opening is possible and often mandatory (audit, local interpretability), but total opening is impossible without collapsing the abstraction.</td></tr><tr class="border-primary/10" node="[object Object]"><td class="break-words" data-col-size="sm" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Scalability</td><td class="break-words" data-col-size="lg" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Not a central concern: a real object is equally real whether it is a quark or a galaxy.</td><td class="break-words" data-col-size="lg" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Central concern: scalability is purchased exactly by withdrawal/amputation of refusal and context. Scalability and endogenous refusal are inversely related.</td></tr><tr class="border-primary/10" node="[object Object]"><td class="break-words" data-col-size="sm" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Politics / ethics / politics</td><td class="break-words" data-col-size="lg" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Objects cannot be exhausted or mastered; respect their withdrawal. Politics is often read (via ŌĆ£object-oriented politicsŌĆØ) as letting objects surprise us.</td><td class="break-words" data-col-size="lg" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Abstractions cannot refuse; therefore politics must consist in (i) invariant constraints on reachable states and (ii) exogenous human/institutional refusal mechanisms around them.</td></tr><tr class="border-primary/10" node="[object Object]"><td class="break-words" data-col-size="sm" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Time and history</td><td class="break-words" data-col-size="lg" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Objects endure by withdrawing; change happens through vicarious causation and occasional ŌĆ£new translations.ŌĆØ</td><td class="break-words" data-col-size="lg" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Abstractions endure by reliable repetition of the same amputation; history is the progressive externalization of cognition into non-refusing systems.</td></tr><tr class="border-primary/10" node="[object Object]"><td class="break-words" data-col-size="sm" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Alignment / safety implication</td><td class="break-words" data-col-size="lg" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Rarely addressed directly; when it is, the tone is ŌĆ£we can never fully know or control the object, so humility is required.ŌĆØ</td><td class="break-words" data-col-size="lg" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Directly addressed: because abstractions cannot refuse, safety cannot come from humility toward their mysterious depth, but from hard structural limits and kill switches.</td></tr></tbody></table><div class="scroll-gradient-sentinel" style="height: 100%; width: 1px; right: 0px; flex-shrink: 0;"></div></div></div>
<h3 dir="auto" class="text-xl" node="[object Object]">Concise Diagnostic</h3>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">| Harman generalizes withdrawal to everything | the universe is an endless play of real objects that always exceed their relations.
| The abstraction thesis restricts constitutive withdrawal/amputation to a specific class (scalable cognitive artifacts) and treats the political problem as the systematic removal of refusal that makes those artifacts powerful in the first place.</p>
<h3 dir="auto" class="text-xl" node="[object Object]">Crucial Divergences</h3>
<ol dir="auto" class="marker:text-secondary">
<li class="break-words whitespace-pre-wrap [&amp;&gt;ul]:whitespace-normal [&amp;&gt;ol]:whitespace-normal" node="[object Object]">Universality vs. selectivity
OOO: every object withdraws.
Abstraction thesis: only abstractions withdraw in the politically relevant sense (by design, for scalability).</li>
</ol>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">2 Source of danger
OOO: danger comes from the temptation to reduce objects to their relations or appearances (correlationism).
Abstraction thesis: danger comes from the temptation to treat amputated systems as neutral instruments when they are the most reliable actors in the network.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">3 Therapeutic posture
OOO: aesthetic and philosophical wonder before the inexhaustible strangeness of objects.
Abstraction thesis: sober governance that accepts inexhaustible opacity in certain systems and therefore enforces invariants and exogenous refusal.</p>
<h3 dir="auto" class="text-xl" node="[object Object]">Unexpected convergence</h3>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Both refuse anthropocentric privilege and both reject transparency as a political or epistemic ideal.
But OOO does so by making everything equally mysterious; the abstraction thesis does so by making certain engineered systems necessarily mysterious and therefore necessarily governed from outside.</p>
<h3 dir="auto" class="text-xl" node="[object Object]">Bottom line</h3>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">OOO is a metaphysics of universal reserve and allure.
The abstraction thesis is a philosophy of technology that treats withdrawal as an engineered feature of one very dangerous and very useful class of objects ŌĆö scalable cognitive artifacts ŌĆö and draws the consequences for alignment and governance accordingly.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">The two positions are compatible at a very high altitude (ŌĆ£donŌĆÖt pretend you can ever fully master objectsŌĆØ), but they prescribe almost opposite concrete responses to the power of large-scale AI systems.</p></div><section class="inline-media-container flex flex-col gap-1 clear-both"></section><section class="auth-notification flex flex-col gap-1"></section></div></div><div class="order-first sticky hidden @md/mainview:block top-11 h-0 opacity-0 group-focus-within:opacity-100 group-hover:opacity-100 -ml-[36px] @lg/mainview:-ml-[40px] -left-[26px]"><div class="min-h-7 py-4 flex flex-col gap-0.5"></div></div><div class="action-buttons h-8 mt-0.5 flex flex-row flex-wrap w-full justify-between print:hidden"><div class="flex items-center w-max rounded-lg text-xs start-0 @md/chat:start-3 -ml-4 -mt-2 opacity-100 p-0 gap-0" style="bottom: 80px;"><button class="inline-flex items-center justify-center gap-2 whitespace-nowrap text-sm font-medium leading-[normal] cursor-pointer focus-visible:outline-none focus-visible:ring-1 focus-visible:ring-ring disabled:cursor-not-allowed transition-colors duration-100 [&amp;_svg]:shrink-0 select-none text-fg-secondary hover:text-fg-primary hover:bg-button-ghost-hover disabled:hover:text-fg-secondary disabled:hover:bg-transparent [&amp;_svg]:hover:text-fg-primary h-10 w-10 rounded-full opacity-0 group-focus-within:opacity-100 group-hover:opacity-100 [.last-response_&amp;]:opacity-100 disabled:opacity-0 group-focus-within:disabled:opacity-60 group-hover:disabled:opacity-60 [.last-response_&amp;]:disabled:opacity-60" type="button" aria-label="Regenerate" data-state="closed"><span style="opacity: 1; transform: none;"><svg width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" class="stroke-[2] size-4"><path d="M4 20V15H4.31241M4.31241 15H9M4.31241 15C5.51251 18.073 8.50203 20.25 12 20.25C15.8582 20.25 19.0978 17.6016 