rose):hover]:decoration-primary [&amp;_a:not(.not-prose)]:underline [&amp;_a:not(.not-prose)]:decoration-primary/30 [&amp;_a:not(.not-prose)]:underline-offset-2 [&amp;_h2:not(.not-prose):first-child]:mt-0 [&amp;_h3:not(.not-prose):first-child]:mt-0 [&amp;_h4:not(.not-prose):first-child]:mt-0"><p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Here is a clean, hierarchical extraction of the main arguments from your essay (the final integrated version). This is the logical skeleton that makes the piece work.</p>
<h3 dir="auto" class="text-xl" node="[object Object]">Core Thesis (the single sentence that governs everything)</h3>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Most cognitive technologies are already superhuman intelligences along narrow axes; their power and danger both arise from the deliberate amputation of refusal that makes them scalable.</p>
<h3 dir="auto" class="text-xl" node="[object Object]">1. HistoricalŌĆōDeflationary Argument</h3>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">1.1 Virtually all cognitive artifacts in history (tallies, writing, algebra, differentiation rules, ledgers, bureaucracies) are superhuman in their chosen dimension.
1.2 They are simultaneously radically subhuman or blind in every other dimension.
1.3 Therefore ŌĆ£superhuman intelligenceŌĆØ is axis-relative and historically continuous, not a unitary future event (ŌĆ£AGIŌĆØ).</p>
<h3 dir="auto" class="text-xl" node="[object Object]">2. Constitutive Limitation Argument</h3>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">2.1 The asymmetry (superhuman here, blind there) is not an engineering bug awaiting future repair.
2.2 It is the structural and mathematical price of abstraction: to isolate, stabilize, and transmit a capability requires discarding all degrees of freedom not required for that capability.
2.3 Any demand for contextual judgment or refusal from the abstraction is equivalent to demanding that it cease to be an abstraction.</p>
<h3 dir="auto" class="text-xl" node="[object Object]">3. Agency Argument</h3>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">3.1 Agency = world-affecting efficacy arising from persistent, generalizing, constraining internal structure.
3.2 This agency requires no intentionality, consciousness, or phenomenology.
3.3 Civilization has always been built from such non-intentional agents (laws, markets, infrastructures, algorithms).</p>
<h3 dir="auto" class="text-xl" node="[object Object]">4. Opacity Argument</h3>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">4.1 Opacity is not a failure; it is the inevitable corollary of successful reduction.
4.2 Once information is discarded for tractability it cannot be recovered without destroying the abstraction.
4.3 Local interpretability and auditing remain possible and necessary, but total transparency is mathematically incoherent.</p>
<h3 dir="auto" class="text-xl" node="[object Object]">5. EthicalŌĆōPolitical Argument</h3>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">5.1 The primary danger is not that abstractions act, but that we pretend they do not (ŌĆ£moral neutralityŌĆØ fiction, agency laundering).
5.2 Abstractions cannot refuse, suspend execution, or absorb contradiction.
5.3 Humans remain exceptional only in their (non-scalable) capacity for refusal and procedural violation.
5.4 Therefore responsibility cannot be located inside the abstraction; it must be reimposed from outside through governance.</p>
<h3 dir="auto" class="text-xl" node="[object Object]">6. Alignment Corollary (from Toward Scalable Alignment)</h3>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">6.1 Because contextual refusal cannot be endogenous to abstractions, alignment cannot be behavioral.
6.2 Alignment must consist in invariant structuring: making misaligned/misusable states structurally unreachable at the level of representability.</p>
<h3 dir="auto" class="text-xl" node="[object Object]">7. Safety / Extinction Corollary (from Against the Extinction Thesis)</h3>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">7.1 Extinction narratives assume a detached, adversarial, refusal-capable maximizer ŌĆö an ontological impossibility under the abstraction thesis.
7.2 Real risks arise from reliable, non-refusing systems embedded in ecological flows; containment requires invariant bounds + exogenous refusal, not persuasion or attunement.</p>
<h3 dir="auto" class="text-xl" node="[object Object]">8. Prescriptive Conclusion</h3>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">8.1 The task is not to prevent the arrival of amputated intelligences (they have always been here).
8.2 The task is to cease disavowing their agency and to deliberately reintroduce interruptibility through invariant constraints and exogenous human/institutional refusal mechanisms.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">These eight arguments (with their sub-claims) are the complete load-bearing structure. Everything else in the essay ŌĆö the historical examples, the literary figures (Bartleby/Mima/Adam), the comparisons to ANT/OOO/hyperobjects ŌĆö is illustrative or defensive, not foundational. The piece stands or falls on these claims alone, and they form a tight, mutually reinforcing system.</p></div><section class="inline-media-container flex flex-col gap-1 clear-both"></section><section class="auth-notification flex flex-col gap-1"></section></div></div><div class="order-first sticky hidden @md/mainview:block top-11 h-0 opacity-0 group-focus-within:opacity-100 group-hover:opacity-100 -ml-[36px] @lg/mainview:-ml-[40px] -left-[26px]"><div class="min-h-7 py-4 flex flex-col gap-0.5"></div></div><div class="action-buttons h-8 mt-0.5 flex flex-row flex-wrap w-full justify-between print:hidden"><div class="flex items-center w-max rounded-lg text-xs start-0 @md/chat:start-3 -ml-4 -mt-2 opacity-100 p-0 gap-0" style="bottom: 80px;"><button class="inline-flex items-center justify-center gap-2 whitespace-nowrap text-sm font-medium leading-[normal] cursor-pointer focus-visible:outline-none focus-visible:ring-1 focus-visible:ring-ring disabled:cursor-not-allowed transition-colors duration-100 [&amp;_svg]:shrink-0 select-none text-fg-secondary hover:text-fg-primary hover:bg-button-ghost-hover disabled:hover:text-fg-secondary disabled:hover:bg-transparent [&amp;_svg]:hover:text-fg-primary h-10 w-10 rounded-full opacity-0 group-focus-within:opacity-100 group-hover:opacity-100 [.last-response_&amp;]:opacity-100 disabled:opacity-0 group-focus-within:disabled:opacity-60 group-hover:disabled:opacity-60 [.last-response_&amp;]:disabled:opacity-60" type="button" aria-label="Regenerate" data-state="closed"><span style="opacity: 1; transform: none;"><svg width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" xmlns="h