<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Appendix A: Formal Definitions and Constraints</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Definition A.1 (Abstraction)</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">An abstraction is a system  that achieves stability, transmissibility, and scalability by mapping a higher-dimensional domain  into a reduced representational space  such that:</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">\dim(R) &lt; \dim(D)</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">and such that the discarded degrees of freedom are not reconstructible from .</p>
<hr>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Definition A.2 (Refusal)</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Refusal is the capacity of a system to suspend, violate, or withdraw from execution without that capacity being determined by the systemŌĆÖs own transition rules.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Formally, a system  has refusal iff there exists a meta-operation  such that:</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">\rho \notin \mathcal{T}_S</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">where  is the transition set governing .</p>
<hr>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Definition A.3 (Structural Agency)</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">A system  has structural agency iff:</p>
<ol dir="auto" class="marker:text-secondary">
<li class="break-words whitespace-pre-wrap [&amp;&gt;ul]:whitespace-normal [&amp;&gt;ol]:whitespace-normal" node="[object Object]">produces persistent effects over time</li>
<li class="break-words whitespace-pre-wrap [&amp;&gt;ul]:whitespace-normal [&amp;&gt;ol]:whitespace-normal" node="[object Object]">those effects generalize beyond specific instances</li>
<li class="break-words whitespace-pre-wrap [&amp;&gt;ul]:whitespace-normal [&amp;&gt;ol]:whitespace-normal" node="[object Object]">those effects constrain downstream states of other systems</li>
</ol>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">No intentionality or phenomenology is required.</p>
<hr>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Appendix B: The Axis-Relativity Theorem</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Theorem B.1 (Axis-Relativity of Superhuman Intelligence)</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">There exists no coherent definition of ŌĆ£superhuman intelligenceŌĆØ that is both unitary and historically discontinuous.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Proof (Sketch)</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Let  denote unaided human capacity.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">For any cognitive dimension  (e.g. memory, numerosity, symbolic manipulation), there exists an abstraction  such that:</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">\text{capacity}(A_d, d) &gt; \text{capacity}(H, d)</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">while for all :</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">\text{capacity}(A_d, d') \ll \text{capacity}(H, d')</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Thus intelligence enhancements are dimension-specific and asymmetric.
Therefore ŌĆ£superhuman intelligenceŌĆØ is axis-relative and historically continuous. ŌłÄ</p>
<hr>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Corollary B.1.1 (Deflation of AGI Rupture)</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">The notion of AGI as a singular ontological threshold is incoherent.</p>
<hr>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Appendix C: The Constitutive Limitation Theorem</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Theorem C.1 (Constitutive Limitation of Abstraction)</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">No abstraction can retain full contextual judgment or refusal without ceasing to be scalable.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Proof (Sketch)</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">By Definition A.1, abstraction requires irreversible dimensional reduction.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Refusal (Definition A.2) requires access to context beyond the abstractionŌĆÖs representational space.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Reintroducing that context requires reconstructing discarded degrees of freedom, which implies:</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">\dim(R) \rightarrow \dim(D)</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">destroying scalability.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Therefore refusal cannot be endogenous to abstraction. ŌłÄ</p>
<hr>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Corollary C.1.1 (Impossibility of Endogenous Refusal)</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Any system that can refuse is not a scalable abstraction.</p>
<hr>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Appendix D: The Non-Intentional Agency Theorem</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Theorem D.1 (Agency Without Intentionality)</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">A system may possess agency without possessing intentional states.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Proof (Sketch)</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">By Definition A.3, agency depends only on persistent, generalizing constraint propagation.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Let  be a system such that:</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">S : X \rightarrow Y</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">where  constrains future states of  or other systems.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Intentionality is neither required nor implied by this mapping.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Thus non-intentional systems (laws, markets, algorithms) possess genuine agency. ŌłÄ</p>
<hr>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Corollary D.1.1 (Historical Continuity of Artificial Agency)</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Civilization has always been constituted by non-intentional agents.</p>
<hr>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Appendix E: The Opacity Necessity Theorem</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Theorem E.1 (Opacity as Mathematical Necessity)</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Total transparency of an abstraction is mathematically incoherent.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Proof (Sketch)</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Let  be a lossy abstraction mapping.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">If transparency requires reconstructing  from , then  must be injective.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">But injectivity contradicts dimensional reduction.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Therefore full transparency is impossible without collapsing abstraction. ŌłÄ</p>
<hr>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Corollary E.1.1 (Bounded Interpretability)</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Local interpretability is possible; total interpretability is not.</p>
<hr>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Appendix F: The Externality of Responsibility Theorem</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Theorem F.1 (Responsibility Cannot Be Internal)</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Responsibility for abstraction-driven agency cannot reside within the abstraction itself.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Proof (Sketch)</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">By Theorem C.1, abstractions cannot refuse.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">By Theorem D.1, abstractions act.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Responsibility requires refusal (the ability to suspend or alter execution).</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Therefore responsibility must be imposed externally by agents capable of refusal. ŌłÄ</p>
<hr>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Corollary F.1.1 (Negative Human Exceptionalism)</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Humans are exceptional only in possessing non-scalable refusal.</p>
<hr>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Appendix G: The Invariant Alignment Theorem</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">(from Toward Scalable Alignment*)*</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Theorem G.1 (Invariant Alignment)</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Alignment of abstractions must be structural, not behavioral.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Proof (Sketch)</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Behavioral alignment presupposes contextual judgment at execution time.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">By Corollary C.1.1, abstractions cannot supply such judgment.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Therefore alignment must consist in invariant constraints on representable states:</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">\mathcal{R}_{bad} = \varnothing</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">where  denotes misaligned state representations. ŌłÄ</p>
<hr>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Corollary G.1.1 (Unreachability Criterion)</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">A system is aligned iff misaligned states are structurally unreachable.</p>
<hr>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Appendix H: The Extinction Impossibility Theorem</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">(from Against the Extinction Thesis*)*</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Theorem H.1 (Extinction Maximizer Impossibility)</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">A detached, adversarial, refusal-capable superintelligence is ontologically impossible.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Proof (Sketch)</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Such an agent would require:</p>
<ol dir="auto" class="marker:text-secondary">
<li class="break-words whitespace-pre-wrap [&amp;&gt;ul]:whitespace-normal [&amp;&gt;ol]:whitespace-normal" node="[object Object]">global unification</li>
<li class="break-words whitespace-pre-wrap [&amp;&gt;ul]:whitespace-normal [&amp;&gt;ol]:whitespace-normal" node="[object Object]">refusal capacity</li>
<li class="break-words whitespace-pre-wrap [&amp;&gt;ul]:whitespace-normal [&amp;&gt;ol]:whitespace-normal" node="[object Object]">scalable optimization</li>
</ol>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">But refusal is non-scalable (Corollary C.1.1).</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Thus the hypothesized agent cannot exist. ŌłÄ</p>
<hr>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Corollary H.1.1 (Real Risk Characterization)</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Existential risk arises from persistent, non-refusing systems embedded in ecological flows.</p>
<hr>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Appendix I: The Governance Theorem</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Theorem I.1 (Governance via Exogenous Refusal)</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Safe deployment of abstractions requires invariant constraints plus exogenous refusal mechanisms.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Proof (Sketch)</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">From F.1 responsibility is external.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">From G.1 alignment is invariant.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Therefore governance must combine:</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">structural unreachability</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">institutional interruptibility</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">ŌłÄ</p>
<hr>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Appendix J: Meta-Theorem (Closure)</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Meta-Theorem J.1</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Abstraction, agency, opacity, alignment, and extinction risk form a single closed system governed by the non-scalability of refusal.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Any attempt to modify one element without modifying the others is incoherent.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">ŌłÄ</p>
<hr>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Final Note (for the paper)</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">These appendices are not ornamental.
They close the system.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Any critic must now attack:</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">the definition of abstraction</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">the definition of refusal</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">or the link between scalability and reduction</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Everything else follows by necessity.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">If you want next:</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">a symbolic logic version,</p>
